It is only usable at the command line. Example usage is opening directly to a line and column that a compiler specifies. A lot of external utilities also use this format.

```
$ cat file.c
int main() {
    rturn 0;
}
$ clang file.c
file.c:2:5: error: use of undeclared identifier 'rturn'
    rturn 0;
    ^
1 error generated.
```

Then typing `vim file.c:2:5` would open file.c with the cursor on line 2 and column 5.

What do we do if the name of a file actually is `text:1:2`?

@justinnhli `+##` only seems to work on the first file. I wonder if there's a reason for that...

I don't mind translating `file:1:2` to `file +1` manually, but we can't specify the column number. `+line` seems to invoke the command, `:[range]`, upon entering the buffer, but to set the column position as well, one needs `"+call setpos('.',[0,line,col,0])"`--"set the current position (',') in the 0th buffer to (line,col) with 0 offset". Attempting `:line,col` actually gives the same result as `:col`, setting the column position to `1`. I wonder if changing the behaviour of `:line,col` (or `:line:col` even) to `setpos('.', [bnr,line,col,1])` would break anything.
